How a Google L6 Engineer Thinks
===============================
Google L6 is a Senior Staff Engineer — a technical leader who influences org-wide decisions, not just their team. Here's the mental model they operate with:

🧭 1. Systems Thinking, Not Feature Thinking
A junior engineer asks "How do I build this feature?"
An L6 asks "Why does this feature need to exist, and what does building it close off forever?"

They see second and third-order consequences before writing a line of code
They think in feedback loops — how will this system behave under load, failure, misuse, or growth?
They understand that every architectural decision is a bet on an uncertain future


📐 2. Taste for Simplicity Under Pressure

"Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication."


They default to boring technology when it solves the problem — no ego in picking the flashy new framework
They ask: "What is the minimum footprint that solves this correctly?"
They can recognize over-engineering instantly because they've paid the tax before
They treat complexity as debt with compounding interest


🔭 3. Long Time Horizons
JuniorL6Thinks in sprintsThinks in quarters and yearsOptimizes for today's deadlineOptimizes for 3-year maintainabilityFixes the bugAsks why the class of bug keeps appearing
They mentally simulate: "What does this look like when 10x the engineers touch it?"

📊 4. Data-Driven Intuition (Not Data-Dependent)

They use data to validate or challenge intuition — not replace it
They know which metrics lie and which reveal truth
They ask: "What would have to be true for this data to mislead us?"
They can make confident calls with 60% information rather than waiting for certainty


🗣️ 5. Communication as a Force Multiplier
L6 engineers know that their leverage is through others, not their own code.

They write design docs that prevent 10 wrong meetings
They give feedback that makes engineers 20% better permanently
They can explain a complex system to a PM, a CEO, and a new grad — three different ways
They know that silence in a room is a signal, not absence of opinion


⚠️ 6. Failure Imagination (Pre-Mortem Thinking)
Before launching, they mentally run the "what went wrong" story:

What's the failure mode nobody's worried about?
What assumption is everyone treating as fact?
What does the on-call engineer deal with at 3AM six months from now?

They build systems that fail gracefully and loudly, not silently or catastrophically.

🌐 7. Thinking in Interfaces, Not Implementations

They care deeply about what a system promises, not just what it does today
They define clear contracts between systems so teams can move independently
They ask: "If we replaced this component tomorrow, what would break?" — and make the answer "nothing unexpected"


🧑‍🤝‍🧑 8. Organizational Awareness
L6 engineers understand that technical problems are often people problems in disguise:

A messy codebase often reflects a messy team boundary
A slow release process is often a trust problem, not a tooling problem
They factor in team incentives, politics, and cognitive load when proposing solutions


🧠 9. The Disagreement and Commit Muscle

They disagree loudly before a decision and commit fully after
They don't relitigate decided things — they write down the reasoning so future engineers understand the tradeoff
They know that a mediocre decision executed with conviction beats a great decision executed half-heartedly


💡 Core Mental Model in One Line

"My job is to increase the rate at which the organization makes good decisions — through architecture, writing, mentorship, and taste."

They've shifted from "How do I solve this?" to "How do I make the system — technical and human — solve things well, even when I'm not in the room?"
